    <statement><div><p>The <alert>period</alert> (<m>T</m>) of a swinging pendulum is the reciprocal of its <alert>frequency</alert> (<m>f</m>). The relationship is given by the formula:</p>
<m>T = \frac{1}{f} </m>

<p>This means: if you know the frequency, you can find the period by taking <alert>1 divided by the frequency</alert>.</p><p>A digital sensor measures a pendulum's frequency as <alert><m>{4.929}</m> swings per second (Hz)</alert>.</p>
<p>Use the <alert>table of reciprocals</alert> provided to calculate the pendulum's period in seconds.</p>
<p>Period (<m>T</m>) <m>=</m> <fillin characters="7" name="ans1"/> s </p></div></statement>
    <solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>We are asked to find the period of a pendulum. The period <alert>T</alert> is the reciprocal of the frequency:</p>

<me> T = \frac{1}{{4.929}} </me>

<p>We use a mathematical table of reciprocals to find this value:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Locate the row corresponding to <alert><m>{4.9}</m></alert> in the column labelled <m>x</m>.</li>
  <li>Move across to the main column headed <alert><m>{2}</m></alert>. The value at this intersection is <alert><m>{0.2033}</m></alert>.</li>
  <li>Continue along the same row to the "SUBTRACT" (Mean Difference) column headed <alert><m>{9}</m></alert>. The value here corresponds to <alert><m>{4}</m></alert>, representing 0.000<m>{4}</m>.</li>
  <li>Subtract the mean difference from the main table value.  
      (We subtract because the reciprocal function <m>y = 1/x</m> decreases as <m>x</m> increases.)</li>
</ol>

<p>Calculation:</p>
<me> {0.2033} - 0.000{4} = {0.2029} </me>

<p>Thus, the period of the pendulum is <alert><m>{0.2029}</m> seconds</alert>.</p></div></solution>
    <answer><p><m>0.2029</m></p></answer>
